            "text": {
              "status": "generated",
              "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">STEMI, treated with PCI</div>"
            },
            "code": {
              "coding": [
                {
                  "system": "http://loinc.org",
                  "code": "67781-5",
                  "display": "Summarization of encounter note"
                }
              ]
            },
            "title": "Synthesis"
          },
          {
            "text": {
              "status": "generated",
              "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">Dear colleague, I am writing to inform you about the hospital course of your 90-year-old female patient admitted on 02/05/2005 with acute ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) of the anterior wall. On admission, ECG confirmed anterior ST elevations, and troponin levels were significantly elevated, consistent with acute anterior STEMI. The patient was promptly transferred to the cardiac catheterization laboratory, where coronary angiography revealed significant occlusion of the left anterior descending artery. Primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) was successfully performed with restoration of TIMI III flow. The patient was monitored in the cardiac care unit post-procedure and remained hemodynamically stable. She was discharged on 03/05/2005 on dual antiplatelet therapy, statin, ACE inhibitor, and beta-blocker. Close outpatient cardiology follow-up is strongly recommended given her age and clinical complexity.</div>"
            },
            "code": {
